Since Stash 3.4.1, the logs are spammed with hazelcast WARN messages such as this:
{noformat}com.hazelcast.web.SessionListener The com.hazelcast.web.WebFilter could not be found. com.hazelcast.web.SessionListener should be paired with a com.hazelcast.web.WebFilter.{noformat}

This has made troubleshooting logs more difficult as logs get very huge.

Temporary workaround is to add the following to stash-config.properties and restart Stash:
{{logging.logger.com.hazelcast.web.SessionListener=ERROR}}

It's still possible to see error messages such as:

{code}
2014-11-01 10:08:57,402 WARN  [http-nio-9080-exec-1] *17G4IGOx608x756775x2 1ijresm 121.44.5.154,172.24.36.105,172.24.12.146,172.24.12.181 "GET /rest/api/1.0/projects/BUILDENG/repos/buildeng-puppet/pull-requests HTTP/1.1" o.s.s.w.a.s.ChangeSessionIdAuthenticationStrategy Your servlet container did not change the session ID when a new session was created. You will not be adequately protected against session-fixation attacks
{code}

The instructions to resolve a conflicted pull request are wrong, and recommend merging the target branch into the source branch. This is backwards, and would result in an unintentional merge if followed. I have to tell our devs to ignore these instructions.

A case study:

I create a pull request from release/1.0 -> feature/develop/1.1 to pick up bugfixes that have been committed to the release branch only. When conflicts arise, I am still seeing instructions like this:

{quote}
This pull request has conflicts. You must resolve the conflicts before you can merge:
Step 1: Fetch the changes (saving the target branch as FETCH_HEAD).
{code}
git fetch origin feature/develop/1.1
{code}
Step 2: Checkout the source branch and merge in the changes from the target branch. Resolve conflicts.
{code}
git checkout release/1.0 
git merge FETCH_HEAD
{code}
Step 3: After the merge conflicts are resolved, stage the changes accordingly, commit the changes and push.
{code}
git commit
git push origin HEAD
{code}
Step 4: Merge the updated pull request.
{quote}

These instructions suggest a merge from feature/develop/1.1 -> release/1.0 which is definitely not the behavior I want. I am trying to bring back bugfixes, not bring my 1.1 code into the 1.0 release branch.

Also see STASH-3083

I work on a team that uses Objective-C code in stash, so sometimes I want to use an @ symbol within my comment as part of a source code snippet:

{noformat}
[NSString stringWithFormat:@"%lld apple pies", [applePie count]]
{noformat}

So I escape it using Markdown backticks for an inline code section:

{noformat}
`[NSString stringWithFormat:@"%lld apple pies", [applePie count]]`
{noformat}

However, this gets interpreted as an @mention, and the quotes get removed from display. It renders like this:

{noformat}
[NSString stringWithFormat:@%lld apple pies, [applePie count]]
{noformat}

The workaround is to include the quotes twice in the input:

{noformat}
`[NSString stringWithFormat:@""%lld apple pies"", [applePie count]]`
{noformat}

Tested in Firefox Aurora (35.0a2), Opera Developer (26), and Chrome Beta (40).

